{"title_page": "Giannina Braschi", "text_new": "{{short description|Puerto Rican writer}}\n{{Essay|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|image =\n| name         = Giannina Braschi\n| caption      =\n| pseudonym    =\n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1953|02|05}}\n| birth_place  = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Puerto Rico]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| occupation   = Poet, novelist, essayist, dramatist\n| nationality  = Puerto Rican, American\n| period       = 1981\u2013present\n| genre        = Poetry, fiction, drama, novel, political philosophy \n| subject      = [[Immigration]], [[independence]], [[terrorism]], inspiration, Latin America, [[Puerto Rico]], [[revolution]], war, love, [[American imperialism]], New York, democracy, [[September 11 attacks]]\n| movement     = [[Postmodernism]], [[postcolonialism]], spoken word, [[nuyorican]], post-boom, [[McOndo]]\n| notableworks = ''[[Yo-Yo Boing!]]''; [[Empire of Dreams (book)]]; ''[[United States of Banana]]''\n| spouse       =\n| partner      =\n| children     =\n| relatives    = Miguel Braschi, brother\n| awards       = National Endowment for the Arts Fellowship, PEN/Open Book Award, New York Foundation for the Arts, Danforth Scholarship, Ford Foundation Fellowship, Rutgers University Faculty Grant\n| signature    =\n| website      = {{URL|gianninabraschi.wordpress.com}}\n}}\n'''Giannina Braschi''' (born February 5, 1953) is a [[Puerto Rico|Puerto Rican]] writer based in [[New York City]]. Her notable tiles include  ''[[Empire of Dreams]] (1988)', ''[[Yo-Yo Boing!]]'' (1998), and ''[[United States of Banana]]'' (2011). \n\nThough categorized as novels, her cross-genre works are experimental and incorporate elements of poetry, drama, fiction, and political philosophy. Braschi writes in Spanish, Spanglish, and English. Her work explores the enculturation journey of Hispanic immigrants. Her work dramatizes the three political options of Puerto Rico: independence, colony, and state.<ref>Aldama, Frederick, and Christopher Gonz\u00e1lez. Latinx Studies: The Key Concepts. Routledge, 2018.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Perisic |first1=Alexandra |title=Precarious Crossings: Immigration, Neoliberalism, and the Atlantic |date=November 2020 |publisher=The Ohio State University Press |location=Ohio |isbn=978-0-8142-5552-0 |pages=152-173 |url=https://kb.osu.edu/handle/1811/88397}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\n\nGiannina Braschi was born in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]] in 1953 to an upper class family of Italian ancestry.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Christopher |title=Permissible Narratives: The Promise of Latino/a Literature |date=2017 |publisher=The Ohio State University Press |location=Ohio |isbn=978-0-8142-5441-7 |pages=93-95 |url=https://ohiostatepress.org/books/titles/9780814213506.html}}</ref> In 1966, she ranked first place in the US Tennis Association's national tournament and became the youngest female tennis player to win the Women's Division on the island. Her father Euripides (called \"Pilo\") Braschi was also a tennis champion. Braschi was a founding member of the [[San Juan Children's Choir]] (''\"Coro de ni\u00f1os de San Juan\"'') under music director Evy Lucio. She worked as a fashion model during her teen years.<ref>D\u00edaz, Carmen Graciela, \"Avion, sol y libertad,\" ''El Nuevo Dia'', 17 November 2011 [http://www.elnuevodia.com/avion,solylibertad-1122361.html]</ref> In the late 1970s, she studied literature and philosophy in Madrid, Rome, Paris and London, before she settled in [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nbclatino.com/2013/08/25/summer-reads-brilliant-takes-on-nuyoricans-random-murder-and-narco-literatura/|title=Summer reads: brilliant takes on Nuyoricans, random murder and narco-literatura|first=Claudio Iv\u00e1n|last=Remeseira|date=August 25, 2013|website=NBC Latino}}</ref> \n\n==Academic career==\n\nBraschi obtained a PhD in Hispanic Literatures at [[State University of New York, Stony Brook]] in 1980. She has taught at [[Rutgers University]], [[City University of New York]], and [[Colgate University]], where she served as a Distinguished Chair of Creative Writing. She served as a foreign correspondent for ''Grazie'' magazine. Braschi wrote scholarly essays about writers of the [[Spanish Golden Age]], as well as the vanguard poets of Latin America and Spain. She published a book on the Romantic poet [[Gustavo Adolfo Becquer]] and essays on [[Miguel de Cervantes|Cervantes]], [[Garcilaso de la Vega (poet)|Garcilaso]], [[C\u00e9sar Vallejo]], [[Juan Ramon Jimenez]] and [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perisic |first1=Alexandra |title=Precarious Crossings: Immigration, Neoliberalism, and the Atlantic |date=2019 |publisher=The Ohio State University Press |location=Ohio |isbn=978-0-8142-5552-0 |pages=155-157 |url=https://kb.osu.edu/handle/1811/88397}}</ref> \n\n==Literary career==\n\nBraschi\u2019s work is situated in the Latinx avant-garde, a \"burgeoning body of work that testifies to Latinx writers\u2019 abiding interest in the avant-garde as a means for engaging ideas of material, social relevance\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Riofrio |first1=John |title=Falling for debt: Giannina Braschi, the Latinx avant-garde, and financial terrorism in the United States of Banana |journal=Latino Studies |date=January 28, 2020 |volume=SBN: 1476-3435 |url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1057%2Fs41276-019-00239-2}}</ref>\nBraschi is considered a \"revolutionary voice in contemporary [[Latin American literature]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/bookfest/author/giannina_braschi|title=Giannina Braschi|work=National Book Festival|publisher=Library of Congress|year=2012|quote=\u2019Braschi: one of the most revolutionary voices in Latin America today\u2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=About Giannina Braschi: Book Fest 12|publisher=Library of Congress|date=September 2012|url=https://www.loc.gov/today/cyberlc/feature_wdesc.php?rec=5804|quote=\u2019Braschi, a poet, essayist and novelist often described as cutting-edge, influential and even revolutionary\u2019|work=National Book Festival Transcript and Webcast|location=Washington, DC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|publisher=Publishing Perspectives|title=#BEA11: Books on Display, the Amazon Publishing Booth|first=Hannah|last=Johnson|date=May 26, 2011|url=http://publishingperspectives.com/2011/05/bea-books-amazon-publishing-booth|quote=\u2019Braschi is Puerto Rico's most influential and versatile writer of poetry, fiction, and essays\u2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|publisher=World Literature Today|title='About Giannina Braschi'|date=September\u2013October 2012|location=University of Oklahoma|quote='One of the most revolutionary voices in Latin American'|url=http://www.worldliteraturetoday.com/2012/september/what-read-now-mixed-genre-literature-giannina-braschi|access-date=2012-08-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914075725/http://www.worldliteraturetoday.com/2012/september/what-read-now-mixed-genre-literature-giannina-braschi|archive-date=2012-09-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>  \n\n'''Early Poetry in Spanish'''\n\nIn the 1980s Giannina Braschi entered the [[Nuyorican]] poetry scene with [[spoken word]] performances in Spanish. First published in Barcelona, her poetry collections include ''Asalto al tiempo'' (Assault on Time, 1980), ''La Comedia profana'' (Profane Comedy, 1985), and ''El Imperio de los sue\u00f1os'' (Empire of Dreams, 1988).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cruz-Malave |first1=Arnaldo |title=Under the Skirt of Liberty: Giannina Braschi Rewrites Empire |journal=American Quarterly |date=September 1, 2014 |volume=66 |pages=801-818 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/283628679_Under_the_Skirt_of_Liberty_Giannina_Braschi_Rewrites_Empire/citation/download}}</ref>\n\nNew York City is the site and subject of much of her poetry. In a climactic episode of [[Braschi's Empire of Dreams|Braschi's ''Empire of Dreams'']], \"[[Pastoral]] or the Inquisition of Memories\", shepherds invade [[Fifth Avenue|5th Avenue]] during the [[Puerto Rican Day Parade]] and take over the City of New York; the shepherds ring the bells of [[St. Patrick's Cathedral, New York|St. Patrick's Cathedral]], and seize the observation deck of the [[Empire State Building]]. Immigrant characters play the role of other characters, swapping names, genders, personal histories, and identities. Feminist poet and scholar [[Alicia Ostriker]] qualifies her gender-bending and genre-blending poetry as having a \"sheer erotic energy that defies definition and dogma.\"<ref>Introduction to Giannina Braschi's ''Empire of Dreams'', Alicia Ostriker, New Haven: Yale University Press, 1994</ref> \n\n'''Spanglish Fiction'''\n\nIn the 1990s, Braschi wrote and performed dramatic dialogues in [[Spanglish]].<ref>''Lengua Fresca'', co-edited by [[Ilan Stavans]] and [[Harold Augenbraum]]</ref> Her code-switching bilingual novel ''[[Yo-Yo Boing!]]'' (1998) explores \"the lived experiences of urban life for Hispanics, as in the case with New York City, and her principal interest is in representing how individuals move in and out of different cultural coordinates, including one so crucial as language.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Foster |first1=David William |title=Review of Yo-Yo Boing! |date=1999 |publisher=Review of Contemporary Fiction |location=McLean, Illinois |pages=202-203}}</ref> The book was written in an era of renewed calls for English-only laws, [[ethnic cleansing]] campaigns, and [[corporate censorship]].<ref>Introduction to Giannina Braschi's ''Yo-Yo Boing!'', Doris Sommer, Harvard University, 1998.</ref> \"For decades, [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] and [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] authors have carried out a linguistic revolution\", noted ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', \"and Giannina Braschi, especially in her novel [[Yo-Yo Boing!]]'', testify to it\".<ref>''The Boston Globe'', \"Spanglish is everywhere now, which is no problema for some, but a pain in the cuello for purists\", by [[Ilan Stavans]], 14 September 2003.</ref>  \n\n'''Political Fiction in English'''\n\nIn 2011, Giannina Braschi published ''[[United States of Banana]]'', her first book written entirely in English.<ref name=\"auto\">Sheeran, Amy, and Amanda M. Smith. \"A Graphic Revolution: Talking Poetry & Politics with Giannina Braschi.\" Chiric\u00f9 Journal: Latina/o Literature, Art, and Culture 2.2 (2018): United State of 3-4.</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://poets.org/poet/giannina-braschi|title=About Giannina Braschi &#124; Academy of American Poets|first=Academy of American|last=Poets|website=poets.org}}</ref> It is a [[postmodern]] work using different genres and techniques to explore cultural and political shifts in the United States and the world after the attacks of [[9/11]]. The work is a critique of 21st-century [[capitalism]], corporate [[censorship]], and the global war on terror. Braschi spoke on a panel on \"The New Censorship\" at the [[PEN International|PEN]] 2012 World Voices Festival where she offered \"a critique of 21st century capitalism in which [she] condemned corporate censorship and control.\"<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|author=Roth, Larry|title=Rushdie Brings PEN Festival to Close|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/07/rushdie-brings-pen-festival-to-close/|date=May 7, 2012}}</ref> \n\nHer work is celebratory of foreign influences.<ref>Braschi, Giannina, \"What to Read Now: Mixed-Genre Literature\", ''World Literature Today,'' September\u2013October 2012 [http://www.worldliteraturetoday.com/2012/september/what-read-now-mixed-genre-literature-giannina-braschi] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914075725/http://www.worldliteraturetoday.com/2012/september/what-read-now-mixed-genre-literature-giannina-braschi |date=2012-09-14 }}</ref>  Braschi stated in ''[[Evergreen Review]]'' that she considered herself \"more French than [[Samuel Beckett|Beckett]], [[Pablo Picasso|Picasso]] and [[Gertrude Stein]]\", and identifies as  the \"granddaughter of [[Alfred Jarry]] and [[Antonin Artaud]], bastard child of [[Samuel Beckett]] and [[James Joyce]], half-sister to [[Heiner M\u00fcller]], kissing cousin of [[Tadeusz Kantor]], and lover of Witkiewicz\".<ref>''The Evergreen Review's 50th Anniversary Edition'', (www.evergreenreview.com), Giannina Braschi, 2007.</ref>\n\n==Adaptions and translations==\n\nBraschi's texts have been adapted into other art forms, including video and photography by [[Michael Somoroff]], painting and sculpture by [[Michael Zansky]], theater play by Juan Pablo Felix, and graphic novel by [[Joakim Lindengren]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Somoroff |first1=Michael |title=Two Crowns of the Egg |url=https://www.lensculture.com/books/14630-michael-somoroff-two-crowns-of-the-egg |website=Lens Culture Magazine |publisher=Damiani |language=English}}</ref><ref>United States of Banana: A Postcolonial Dramatic Fiction, Juan Pablo Felix, Columbia University Stages, New York, 2015</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lindengren |first1=Joakim |title=Image from United States of Banana: A Comic Book, Cobolt, 2017 |journal=Chiric\u00fa Journal: Latina/o Literatures, Arts, and Cultures |date=2018 |volume=vol. 2 no. 2, 2018 |pages=3-4 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/697732/summary}}</ref> Her books have been translated into English by Tess O'Dwyer, into Spanish by Manolo Broncano, and into Swedish by [[Helena Eriksson]] and Hannah Nordenhok.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://poets.org/poet/tess-odwyer|title=About Tess O'Dwyer &#124; Academy of American Poets|first=Academy of American|last=Poets|website=poets.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tranan.nu/bocker/drommarnas-imperium/|title=Dr\u00f6mmarnas imperium}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mignone smith |first1=Amanda |last2=Sheeran |first2=Amy |title=A Graphic Revolution: Talking Poetry & Politics with Giannina Braschi.\u201d |journal=Chiric\u00fa Journal: Latina/o Literatures, Arts, and Cultures |date=Spring 2018 |volume=Vol. 2, No. 2, Spring 2018 |pages=130\u2013142 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.2979/chiricu.2.issue-2 |accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political activism==\n\nBraschi declared the independence of Puerto Rico in [[United States of Banana]] and stated in the press that \"[[Liberty]] is not an option \u2014 it is a human right.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/lalibertadnoesunaopcionesunderecho-1349719/|title=\u2018La libertad no es una opci\u00f3n, es un derecho\u2019|date=September 24, 2012|website=El Nuevo Dia}}</ref> In the 1990s, she protested the United States Navy's bombing exercises in [[Vieques]], along with politicians Rub\u00e9n Berr\u00edos and Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., singers Danny Rivera and Willie Col\u00f3n, and fellow writers Ana Lydia Vega and Rigoberta Mench\u00fa. In July 2019, Braschi lead early marches outside La Fortaleza in Old San Juan to demand the resignation of Puerto Rican Governor [[Ricardo Rossello]], and joined massive manifestations, with singers [[Bad Bunny]], [[Residente]], and [[Ricky Martin]], that led to the Governor's resignation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Figueroa |first1=Jan Javier |title=Diferentes opiniones sobre manifestaciones en Fortaleza Las manifestaciones exigiendo la renuncia al gobernador, Ricardo Rossell\u00f3, continuar\u00e1n ma\u00f1ana a las cinco de la tarde. |url=https://www.elvocero.com/gobierno/diferentes-opiniones-sobre-manifestaciones-en-fortaleza/article_8b643cc4-a821-11e9-b7d8-eb4abf0f4277.html |accessdate=July 16, 2019 |agency=El Vocero |publisher=El Vocero, Puerto Rican News |date=July 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Cortez Chico |first1=Ricardo |last2=Lopez Alicea |first2=Keila |title=Mobilized by Indignation: Demanding the Resignation of Governor Rossello |work=Front Page News Image |agency=El Nuevo Dia |publisher=The Daily News of Puerto Rico |date=July 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\n* ''Estados Unidos de Banana, AmazonCrossing, Madrid, 2015.\n* ''[[United States of Banana]],'' AmazonCrossing, Seattle, 2011.\n* ''[[Yo-Yo Boing!]],'' AmazonCrossing, Seattle, 2011.\n*  ''[[Empire of Dreams]],'' AmazonCrossing, Seattle, 2011.\n* ''El imperio de los sue\u00f1os'', Editorial de la Universidad de Puerto Rico, Rio Piedras, 2000.\n* ''Yo-Yo Boing!'', Latin American Literary Review, Pittsburgh, 1998.\n* ''Empire of Dreams'' (English translation by Tess O'Dwyer), Yale University Press, New Haven/London, 1994.\n* ''El imperio de los sue\u00f1os'', Anthropos Editorial del hombre, Barcelona, 1988.\n* ''Libro de payasos y bufones'', Grafica Uno, Giorgio Upiglio, Milan, 1987.\n* ''La comedia profana'', Anthropos Editorial del hombre, Barcelona, 1985.\n* ''Asalto al tiempo'', Ambitos Literarios, Barcelona, 1980.\n\n==Scholarly works==\n* ''\"Breve tratado del poeta artista\"'', ''Cuadernos Hispanoamericanos,'' No. 433-36, 1986 (an essay on the poetry of [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]]).\n* ''\"La gravedad de la armon\u00eda en \u2018Soledades galer\u00edas y otros pomas\u2019 de Machado,\"'' ''Plural,'' 1983 (an essay on the poetry of [[Antonio Machado]]).\n* ''\"La poes\u00eda de B\u00e9cquer: El tiempo de los objetos o los espacios de la luz\"'', ''Costa Amic,'' Mexico City, 1982 (a scholarly book on the poetry of [[Gustavo Adolfo Becquer]]).\n* ''\"La Metamorfosis del ingenio en la \u00c9gloga III de [[Garcilaso de la Vega (poet)|Garcilaso]],\"'' ''Revista canadiense de estudios hisp\u00e1nicos,'' 1979 (an essay on [[Garcilaso de la Vega (poet)|Garcilaso]]'s third eclogue).\n* ''\"Cinco personajes fugaces en el camino de [[Don Quijote]]\"'', ''Cuadernos Hispanoamericanos,'' No. 328, 1977 (an essay on five fleeting characters in [[Don Quixote]] by [[Miguel de Cervantes|Cervantes]]).\n\n==Awards/honors==\n* Danforth Scholarship\n* [[El Diario La Prensa]]'s Outstanding Women of 1998\n* [[Ford Foundation]] Fellowship\n* [[National Endowment for the Arts]] Fellowship\n* [[New York Foundation for the Arts]] Fellowship\n* Peter S. Reed Foundation/InterAmericas\n* [[PEN American Center]]'s [[PEN/Open Book|Open Book Award]]\n* Instituto de Cultura Puertorrique\u00f1a/grant\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Biography|Literature|Poetry}}\n\n* [[The Society for the Study of Multi-Ethnic Literature of the United States]]\n* [[Experimental literature]]\n* [[Postmodern]]\n* [[Pastoral]]\n* [[Nuyorican Movement]]\n* [[McOndo]]\n* [[Spanglish]]\n*[[Puerto Rican literature]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Ljudmila Mila Popovich (2010). \"Metafictions, Migrations, Metalives: Narrative Innovations and Migrant Women\u2019s Aesthetics in Giannina Braschi and Etel Adnan.\" ''International Journal of the Humanities'' 9:10. pp.&nbsp;117\u2013128.\n* Diane E. Marting (2010). \"[http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/the_global_south/summary/v004/4.1.marting.html New/Nueva York in Giannina Braschi's 'Poetic Egg': Fragile Identity, Postmodernism, and Globalization.]\" ''The Global South'' 4:1.\n* Marc Zimmerman (2011). \"Defending Their Own in the Cold: The Cultural Turns of U.S. Puerto Ricans\", University of Illinois, Chicago.\n* Gonzales, Madelena and Laplace-Claverie, Helene, \u201cMinority Theatre on the Global Stage: Challenging Paradigms from the Margins,\" Cambridge Scholars, Newcastle, England, page xix and pages 255-264, 2012.\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120407021643/http://www.ny1noticias.com/content/principales/pura_politica/149439/giannina-braschi-habla-de-su-novela--united-states-of-banana-] [[NY1 Noticias]] TV program PURA POLITICA, [[Juan Manuel Benitez]], interview in Spanish Giannina Braschi on the political options of Puerto Rico, October 2011.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150402121638/http://www.evergreenreview.com/128/review_us_of_banana.shtml], The Evergreen Review, featuring reviews of \"United States of Banana\" by Cristina Garrigos and Daniela Daniele and videos of Giannina Braschi, November 2011.\n*[http://www.wapa.tv/noticias/especiales/orgullo-boricua--giannina-braschi_20111205213641.html], WAPA TV, \"Escritora puertorrique\u00f1a que poco a poco se ha abierto paso en Estados Unidos\" by Normando Valent\u00edn, December 2011.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090219001002/http://current.com/items/88836867/nuyorican_power.htm \"Nuyorican Power,\"] program on Nuyorican culture, featuring Giannina Braschi, Produced By: Evan B. Stone & Carrie Pyle for [https://web.archive.org/web/20191001195812/https://current.com/ CURRENT TV].\n*{{YouTube|eJ58UuLwsJs}}, television program in Spanish, \"Celebrities desde Nueva York,\" con Alfonso Diaz, featuring Giannina Braschi (on the collapse of the American Empire on September 11), November 2011.\n*[https://archive.org/details/Giannina_Braschi] \"Howdy Amiga Bienvenida,\" audio file of Giannina Braschi reading poems in Stockholm, Ars Interpress, 2006.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120914075725/http://www.worldliteraturetoday.com/2012/september/what-read-now-mixed-genre-literature-giannina-braschi], \"What to Read Now: Mixed-Genre Literature,\" World Literature Today, September\u2013October 2012.\n*\"Ground Zero,\" by Giannina Braschi, featured in [http://www.evergreenreview.com Evergreen Review], edited by [[Barney Rosset]].\n*\"El futuro del idioma Espa\u00f1ol\", Oppenheimer Presenta #276, on YouTube(featuring Director of La Real Academia Espanola Victor, Garcia de la Concha, and author Giannina Braschi).\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120309164326/http://www.evergreenreview.com/112/a_la_vieille/a_la_vieille_1.html \"A la Vieille Russie\"] by Giannina Braschi.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Braschi, Giannina}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican poets]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican women writers]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American novelists]]\n[[Category:Postmodern writers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican women short story writers]]\n[[Category:American anarchists]]\n[[Category:American women short story writers]]\n[[Category:American satirists]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American poets]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American writers]]\n[[Category:American women essayists]]\n[[Category:postmodern feminists]]\n[[Category:Epic poets]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican feminists]]\n[[Category:Women satirists]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican independence activists]]\n[[Category:American women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:National Endowment for the Arts Fellows]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican female tennis players]]\n[[Category:20th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:American political philosophers]]\n[[Category:Continental philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Puerto Rican women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Puerto Rican women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Puerto Rican writer}}\n{{Essay|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|image =\n| name         = Giannina Braschi\n| caption      =\n| pseudonym    =\n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1953|02|05}}\n| birth_place  = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Puerto Rico]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| occupation   = Poet, novelist, essayist, dramatist\n| nationality  = Puerto Rican, American\n| period       = 1981\u2013present\n| genre        = Poetry, fiction, drama, novel, political philosophy \n| subject      = [[Immigration]], [[independence]], [[terrorism]], inspiration, Latin America, [[Puerto Rico]], [[revolution]], war, love, [[American imperialism]], New York, democracy, [[September 11 attacks]]\n| movement     = [[Postmodernism]], [[postcolonialism]], spoken word, [[nuyorican]], post-boom, [[McOndo]]\n| notableworks = ''[[Yo-Yo Boing!]]''; [[Empire of Dreams (book)]]; ''[[United States of Banana]]''\n| spouse       =\n| partner      =\n| children     =\n| relatives    = Miguel Braschi, brother\n| awards       = National Endowment for the Arts Fellowship, PEN/Open Book Award, New York Foundation for the Arts, Danforth Scholarship, Ford Foundation Fellowship, Rutgers University Faculty Grant\n| signature    =\n| website      = {{URL|gianninabraschi.wordpress.com}}\n}}\n'''Giannina Braschi''' (born February 5, 1953) is a [[Puerto Rico|Puerto Rican]] writer based in [[New York City]]. Her notable tiles include  ''[[Empire of Dreams]] (1988)', ''[[Yo-Yo Boing!]]'' (1998), and ''[[United States of Banana]]'' (2011). \n\nThough categorized as novels, her cross-genre works are experimental and incorporate elements of poetry, drama, fiction, and political philosophy. Braschi writes in Spanish, Spanglish, and English. Her work explores the enculturation journey of Hispanic immigrants. Her work dramatizes the three political options of Puerto Rico: independence, colony, and state.<ref>Aldama, Frederick, and Christopher Gonz\u00e1lez. Latinx Studies: The Key Concepts. Routledge, 2018.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Perisic |first1=Alexandra |title=Precarious Crossings: Immigration, Neoliberalism, and the Atlantic |date=November 2020 |publisher=The Ohio State University Press |location=Ohio |isbn=978-0-8142-5552-0 |pages=152-173 |url=https://kb.osu.edu/handle/1811/88397}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\n\nGiannina Braschi was born in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]] in 1953 to an upper class family of Italian ancestry.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Christopher |title=Permissible Narratives: The Promise of Latino/a Literature |date=2017 |publisher=The Ohio State University Press |location=Ohio |isbn=978-0-8142-5441-7 |pages=93-95 |url=https://ohiostatepress.org/books/titles/9780814213506.html}}</ref> In 1966, she ranked first place in the US Tennis Association's national tournament and became the youngest female tennis player to win the Women's Division on the island. Her father Euripides (called \"Pilo\") Braschi was also a tennis champion. Braschi was a founding member of the [[San Juan Children's Choir]] (''\"Coro de ni\u00f1os de San Juan\"'') under music director Evy Lucio. She worked as a fashion model during her teen years.<ref>D\u00edaz, Carmen Graciela, \"Avion, sol y libertad,\" ''El Nuevo Dia'', 17 November 2011 [http://www.elnuevodia.com/avion,solylibertad-1122361.html]</ref> In the late 1970s, she studied literature and philosophy in Madrid, Rome, Paris and London, before she settled in [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nbclatino.com/2013/08/25/summer-reads-brilliant-takes-on-nuyoricans-random-murder-and-narco-literatura/|title=Summer reads: brilliant takes on Nuyoricans, random murder and narco-literatura|first=Claudio Iv\u00e1n|last=Remeseira|date=August 25, 2013|website=NBC Latino}}</ref> \n\n==Academic career==\n\nBraschi obtained a PhD in Hispanic Literatures at [[State University of New York, Stony Brook]] in 1980. She has taught at [[Rutgers University]], [[City University of New York]], and [[Colgate University]], where she served as a Distinguished Chair of Creative Writing. She served as a foreign correspondent for ''Grazie'' magazine. Braschi wrote scholarly essays about writers of the [[Spanish Golden Age]], as well as the vanguard poets of Latin America and Spain. She published a book on the Romantic poet [[Gustavo Adolfo Becquer]] and essays on [[Miguel de Cervantes|Cervantes]], [[Garcilaso de la Vega (poet)|Garcilaso]], [[C\u00e9sar Vallejo]], [[Juan Ramon Jimenez]] and [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perisic |first1=Alexandra |title=Precarious Crossings: Immigration, Neoliberalism, and the Atlantic |date=2019 |publisher=The Ohio State University Press |location=Ohio |isbn=978-0-8142-5552-0 |pages=155-157 |url=https://kb.osu.edu/handle/1811/88397}}</ref> \n\n==Literary career==\n\nBraschi\u2019s work is situated in the Latinx avant-garde, a \"burgeoning body of work that testifies to Latinx writers\u2019 abiding interest in the avant-garde as a means for engaging ideas of material, social relevance\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Riofrio |first1=John |title=Falling for debt: Giannina Braschi, the Latinx avant-garde, and financial terrorism in the United States of Banana |journal=Latino Studies |date=January 28, 2020 |volume=SBN: 1476-3435 |url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1057%2Fs41276-019-00239-2}}</ref>\nBraschi is considered a \"revolutionary voice in contemporary [[Latin American literature]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/bookfest/author/giannina_braschi|title=Giannina Braschi|work=National Book Festival|publisher=Library of Congress|year=2012|quote=\u2019Braschi: one of the most revolutionary voices in Latin America today\u2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=About Giannina Braschi: Book Fest 12|publisher=Library of Congress|date=September 2012|url=https://www.loc.gov/today/cyberlc/feature_wdesc.php?rec=5804|quote=\u2019Braschi, a poet, essayist and novelist often described as cutting-edge, influential and even revolutionary\u2019|work=National Book Festival Transcript and Webcast|location=Washington, DC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|publisher=Publishing Perspectives|title=#BEA11: Books on Display, the Amazon Publishing Booth|first=Hannah|last=Johnson|date=May 26, 2011|url=http://publishingperspectives.com/2011/05/bea-books-amazon-publishing-booth|quote=\u2019Braschi is Puerto Rico's most influential and versatile writer of poetry, fiction, and essays\u2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|publisher=World Literature Today|title='About Giannina Braschi'|date=September\u2013October 2012|location=University of Oklahoma|quote='One of the most revolutionary voices in Latin American'|url=http://www.worldliteraturetoday.com/2012/september/what-read-now-mixed-genre-literature-giannina-braschi|access-date=2012-08-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914075725/http://www.worldliteraturetoday.com/2012/september/what-read-now-mixed-genre-literature-giannina-braschi|archive-date=2012-09-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>  \n\n'''Early Poetry in Spanish'''\n\nIn the 1980s Giannina Braschi entered the [[Nuyorican]] poetry scene with [[spoken word]] performances in Spanish. First published in Barcelona, her poetry collections include ''Asalto al tiempo'' (Assault on Time, 1980), ''La Comedia profana'' (Profane Comedy, 1985), and ''El Imperio de los sue\u00f1os'' (Empire of Dreams, 1988).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cruz-Malave |first1=Arnaldo |title=Under the Skirt of Liberty: Giannina Braschi Rewrites Empire |journal=American Quarterly |date=September 1, 2014 |volume=66 |pages=801-818 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/283628679_Under_the_Skirt_of_Liberty_Giannina_Braschi_Rewrites_Empire/citation/download}}</ref>\n\nNew York City is the site and subject of much of her poetry. In a climactic episode of [[Braschi's Empire of Dreams|Braschi's ''Empire of Dreams'']], \"[[Pastoral]] or the Inquisition of Memories\", shepherds invade [[Fifth Avenue|5th Avenue]] during the [[Puerto Rican Day Parade]] and take over the City of New York; the shepherds ring the bells of [[St. Patrick's Cathedral, New York|St. Patrick's Cathedral]], and seize the observation deck of the [[Empire State Building]]. Immigrant characters play the role of other characters, swapping names, genders, personal histories, and identities. Feminist poet and scholar [[Alicia Ostriker]] qualifies her gender-bending and genre-blending poetry as having a \"sheer erotic energy that defies definition and dogma.\"<ref>Introduction to Giannina Braschi's ''Empire of Dreams'', Alicia Ostriker, New Haven: Yale University Press, 1994</ref> \n\n'''Spanglish Fiction'''\n\nIn the 1990s, Braschi wrote and performed dramatic dialogues in [[Spanglish]].<ref>''Lengua Fresca'', co-edited by [[Ilan Stavans]] and [[Harold Augenbraum]]</ref> Her code-switching bilingual novel ''[[Yo-Yo Boing!]]'' (1998) explores \"the lived experiences of urban life for Hispanics, as in the case with New York City, and her principal interest is in representing how individuals move in and out of different cultural coordinates, including one so crucial as language.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Foster |first1=David William |title=Review of Yo-Yo Boing! |date=1999 |publisher=Review of Contemporary Fiction |location=McLean, Illinois |pages=202-203}}</ref> The book was written in an era of renewed calls for English-only laws, [[ethnic cleansing]] campaigns, and [[corporate censorship]].<ref>Introduction to Giannina Braschi's ''Yo-Yo Boing!'', Doris Sommer, Harvard University, 1998.</ref> \"For decades, [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] and [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] authors have carried out a linguistic revolution\", noted ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', \"and Giannina Braschi, especially in her novel [[Yo-Yo Boing!]]'', testify to it\".<ref>''The Boston Globe'', \"Spanglish is everywhere now, which is no problema for some, but a pain in the cuello for purists\", by [[Ilan Stavans]], 14 September 2003.</ref>  \n\n'''Political Fiction in English'''\n\nIn 2011, Giannina Braschi published ''[[United States of Banana]]'', her first book written entirely in English.<ref name=\"auto\">Sheeran, Amy, and Amanda M. Smith. \"A Graphic Revolution: Talking Poetry & Politics with Giannina Braschi.\" Chiric\u00f9 Journal: Latina/o Literature, Art, and Culture 2.2 (2018): United State of 3-4.</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://poets.org/poet/giannina-braschi|title=About Giannina Braschi &#124; Academy of American Poets|first=Academy of American|last=Poets|website=poets.org}}</ref> It is a [[postmodern]] work using different genres and techniques to explore cultural and political shifts in the United States and the world after the attacks of [[9/11]]. The work is a critique of 21st-century [[capitalism]], corporate [[censorship]], and the global war on terror. Braschi spoke on a panel on \"The New Censorship\" at the [[PEN International|PEN]] 2012 World Voices Festival where she offered \"a critique of 21st century capitalism in which [she] condemned corporate censorship and control.\"<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|author=Roth, Larry|title=Rushdie Brings PEN Festival to Close|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/07/rushdie-brings-pen-festival-to-close/|date=May 7, 2012}}</ref> \n\nHer work is celebratory of foreign influences.<ref>Braschi, Giannina, \"What to Read Now: Mixed-Genre Literature\", ''World Literature Today,'' September\u2013October 2012 [http://www.worldliteraturetoday.com/2012/september/what-read-now-mixed-genre-literature-giannina-braschi] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914075725/http://www.worldliteraturetoday.com/2012/september/what-read-now-mixed-genre-literature-giannina-braschi |date=2012-09-14 }}</ref>  Braschi stated in ''[[Evergreen Review]]'' that she considered herself \"more French than [[Samuel Beckett|Beckett]], [[Pablo Picasso|Picasso]] and [[Gertrude Stein]]\", and identifies as  the \"granddaughter of [[Alfred Jarry]] and [[Antonin Artaud]], bastard child of [[Samuel Beckett]] and [[James Joyce]], half-sister to [[Heiner M\u00fcller]], kissing cousin of [[Tadeusz Kantor]], and lover of Witkiewicz\".<ref>''The Evergreen Review's 50th Anniversary Edition'', (www.evergreenreview.com), Giannina Braschi, 2007.</ref>\n\n==Adaptions and translations==\n\nBraschi's texts have been adapted into other art forms, including video and photography by [[Michael Somoroff]], painting and sculpture by [[Michael Zansky]], theater play by Juan Pablo Felix, and graphic novel by [[Joakim Lindengren]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Somoroff |first1=Michael |title=Two Crowns of the Egg |url=https://www.lensculture.com/books/14630-michael-somoroff-two-crowns-of-the-egg |website=Lens Culture Magazine |publisher=Damiani |language=English}}</ref><ref>United States of Banana: A Postcolonial Dramatic Fiction, Juan Pablo Felix, Columbia University Stages, New York, 2015</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lindengren |first1=Joakim |title=Image from United States of Banana: A Comic Book, Cobolt, 2017 |journal=Chiric\u00fa Journal: Latina/o Literatures, Arts, and Cultures |date=2018 |volume=vol. 2 no. 2, 2018 |pages=3-4 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/697732/summary}}</ref> Her books have been translated into English by Tess O'Dwyer, into Spanish by Manolo Broncano, and into Swedish by [[Helena Eriksson]] and Hannah Nordenhok<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://poets.org/poet/tess-odwyer|title=About Tess O'Dwyer &#124; Academy of American Poets|first=Academy of American|last=Poets|website=poets.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tranan.nu/bocker/drommarnas-imperium/|title=Dr\u00f6mmarnas imperium}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mignone smith |first1=Amanda |last2=Sheeran |first2=Amy |title=A Graphic Revolution: Talking Poetry & Politics with Giannina Braschi.\u201d |journal=Chiric\u00fa Journal: Latina/o Literatures, Arts, and Cultures |date=Spring 2018 |volume=Vol. 2, No. 2, Spring 2018 |pages=130\u2013142 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.2979/chiricu.2.issue-2 |accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political activism==\n\nBraschi declared the independence of Puerto Rico in [[United States of Banana]] and stated in the press that \"[[Liberty]] is not an option \u2014 it is a human right.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/lalibertadnoesunaopcionesunderecho-1349719/|title=\u2018La libertad no es una opci\u00f3n, es un derecho\u2019|date=September 24, 2012|website=El Nuevo Dia}}</ref> In the 1990s, she protested the United States Navy's bombing exercises in [[Vieques]], along with politicians Rub\u00e9n Berr\u00edos and Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., singers Danny Rivera and Willie Col\u00f3n, and fellow writers Ana Lydia Vega and Rigoberta Mench\u00fa. In July 2019, Braschi lead early marches outside La Fortaleza in Old San Juan to demand the resignation of Puerto Rican Governor [[Ricardo Rossello]], and joined massive manifestations, with singers [[Bad Bunny]], [[Residente]], and [[Ricky Martin]], that led to the Governor's resignation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Figueroa |first1=Jan Javier |title=Diferentes opiniones sobre manifestaciones en Fortaleza Las manifestaciones exigiendo la renuncia al gobernador, Ricardo Rossell\u00f3, continuar\u00e1n ma\u00f1ana a las cinco de la tarde. |url=https://www.elvocero.com/gobierno/diferentes-opiniones-sobre-manifestaciones-en-fortaleza/article_8b643cc4-a821-11e9-b7d8-eb4abf0f4277.html |accessdate=July 16, 2019 |agency=El Vocero |publisher=El Vocero, Puerto Rican News |date=July 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Cortez Chico |first1=Ricardo |last2=Lopez Alicea |first2=Keila |title=Mobilized by Indignation: Demanding the Resignation of Governor Rossello |work=Front Page News Image |agency=El Nuevo Dia |publisher=The Daily News of Puerto Rico |date=July 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\n* ''Estados Unidos de Banana, AmazonCrossing, Madrid, 2015.\n* ''[[United States of Banana]],'' AmazonCrossing, Seattle, 2011.\n* ''[[Yo-Yo Boing!]],'' AmazonCrossing, Seattle, 2011.\n*  ''[[Empire of Dreams]],'' AmazonCrossing, Seattle, 2011.\n* ''El imperio de los sue\u00f1os'', Editorial de la Universidad de Puerto Rico, Rio Piedras, 2000.\n* ''Yo-Yo Boing!'', Latin American Literary Review, Pittsburgh, 1998.\n* ''Empire of Dreams'' (English translation by Tess O'Dwyer), Yale University Press, New Haven/London, 1994.\n* ''El imperio de los sue\u00f1os'', Anthropos Editorial del hombre, Barcelona, 1988.\n* ''Libro de payasos y bufones'', Grafica Uno, Giorgio Upiglio, Milan, 1987.\n* ''La comedia profana'', Anthropos Editorial del hombre, Barcelona, 1985.\n* ''Asalto al tiempo'', Ambitos Literarios, Barcelona, 1980.\n\n==Scholarly works==\n* ''\"Breve tratado del poeta artista\"'', ''Cuadernos Hispanoamericanos,'' No. 433-36, 1986 (an essay on the poetry of [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]]).\n* ''\"La gravedad de la armon\u00eda en \u2018Soledades galer\u00edas y otros pomas\u2019 de Machado,\"'' ''Plural,'' 1983 (an essay on the poetry of [[Antonio Machado]]).\n* ''\"La poes\u00eda de B\u00e9cquer: El tiempo de los objetos o los espacios de la luz\"'', ''Costa Amic,'' Mexico City, 1982 (a scholarly book on the poetry of [[Gustavo Adolfo Becquer]]).\n* ''\"La Metamorfosis del ingenio en la \u00c9gloga III de [[Garcilaso de la Vega (poet)|Garcilaso]],\"'' ''Revista canadiense de estudios hisp\u00e1nicos,'' 1979 (an essay on [[Garcilaso de la Vega (poet)|Garcilaso]]'s third eclogue).\n* ''\"Cinco personajes fugaces en el camino de [[Don Quijote]]\"'', ''Cuadernos Hispanoamericanos,'' No. 328, 1977 (an essay on five fleeting characters in [[Don Quixote]] by [[Miguel de Cervantes|Cervantes]]).\n\n==Awards/honors==\n* Danforth Scholarship\n* [[El Diario La Prensa]]'s Outstanding Women of 1998\n* [[Ford Foundation]] Fellowship\n* [[National Endowment for the Arts]] Fellowship\n* [[New York Foundation for the Arts]] Fellowship\n* Peter S. Reed Foundation/InterAmericas\n* [[PEN American Center]]'s [[PEN/Open Book|Open Book Award]]\n* Instituto de Cultura Puertorrique\u00f1a/grant\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Biography|Literature|Poetry}}\n\n* [[The Society for the Study of Multi-Ethnic Literature of the United States]]\n* [[Experimental literature]]\n* [[Postmodern]]\n* [[Pastoral]]\n* [[Nuyorican Movement]]\n* [[McOndo]]\n* [[Spanglish]]\n*[[Puerto Rican literature]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Ljudmila Mila Popovich (2010). \"Metafictions, Migrations, Metalives: Narrative Innovations and Migrant Women\u2019s Aesthetics in Giannina Braschi and Etel Adnan.\" ''International Journal of the Humanities'' 9:10. pp.&nbsp;117\u2013128.\n* Diane E. Marting (2010). \"[http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/the_global_south/summary/v004/4.1.marting.html New/Nueva York in Giannina Braschi's 'Poetic Egg': Fragile Identity, Postmodernism, and Globalization.]\" ''The Global South'' 4:1.\n* Marc Zimmerman (2011). \"Defending Their Own in the Cold: The Cultural Turns of U.S. Puerto Ricans\", University of Illinois, Chicago.\n* Gonzales, Madelena and Laplace-Claverie, Helene, \u201cMinority Theatre on the Global Stage: Challenging Paradigms from the Margins,\" Cambridge Scholars, Newcastle, England, page xix and pages 255-264, 2012.\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120407021643/http://www.ny1noticias.com/content/principales/pura_politica/149439/giannina-braschi-habla-de-su-novela--united-states-of-banana-] [[NY1 Noticias]] TV program PURA POLITICA, [[Juan Manuel Benitez]], interview in Spanish Giannina Braschi on the political options of Puerto Rico, October 2011.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150402121638/http://www.evergreenreview.com/128/review_us_of_banana.shtml], The Evergreen Review, featuring reviews of \"United States of Banana\" by Cristina Garrigos and Daniela Daniele and videos of Giannina Braschi, November 2011.\n*[http://www.wapa.tv/noticias/especiales/orgullo-boricua--giannina-braschi_20111205213641.html], WAPA TV, \"Escritora puertorrique\u00f1a que poco a poco se ha abierto paso en Estados Unidos\" by Normando Valent\u00edn, December 2011.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090219001002/http://current.com/items/88836867/nuyorican_power.htm \"Nuyorican Power,\"] program on Nuyorican culture, featuring Giannina Braschi, Produced By: Evan B. Stone & Carrie Pyle for [https://web.archive.org/web/20191001195812/https://current.com/ CURRENT TV].\n*{{YouTube|eJ58UuLwsJs}}, television program in Spanish, \"Celebrities desde Nueva York,\" con Alfonso Diaz, featuring Giannina Braschi (on the collapse of the American Empire on September 11), November 2011.\n*[https://archive.org/details/Giannina_Braschi] \"Howdy Amiga Bienvenida,\" audio file of Giannina Braschi reading poems in Stockholm, Ars Interpress, 2006.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120914075725/http://www.worldliteraturetoday.com/2012/september/what-read-now-mixed-genre-literature-giannina-braschi], \"What to Read Now: Mixed-Genre Literature,\" World Literature Today, September\u2013October 2012.\n*\"Ground Zero,\" by Giannina Braschi, featured in [http://www.evergreenreview.com Evergreen Review], edited by [[Barney Rosset]].\n*\"El futuro del idioma Espa\u00f1ol\", Oppenheimer Presenta #276, on YouTube(featuring Director of La Real Academia Espanola Victor, Garcia de la Concha, and author Giannina Braschi).\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120309164326/http://www.evergreenreview.com/112/a_la_vieille/a_la_vieille_1.html \"A la Vieille Russie\"] by Giannina Braschi.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Braschi, Giannina}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican poets]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican women writers]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American novelists]]\n[[Category:Postmodern writers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican women short story writers]]\n[[Category:American anarchists]]\n[[Category:American women short story writers]]\n[[Category:American satirists]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American poets]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American writers]]\n[[Category:American women essayists]]\n[[Category:postmodern feminists]]\n[[Category:Epic poets]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican feminists]]\n[[Category:Women satirists]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican independence activists]]\n[[Category:American women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:National Endowment for the Arts Fellows]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican female tennis players]]\n[[Category:20th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:American political philosophers]]\n[[Category:Continental philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Puerto Rican women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Puerto Rican women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Greyjoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAdaptions and translations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giannina_Braschi"}
{"title_page": "Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Entertain Me|the Blur song|The Great Escape (Blur album)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Soft Cell]]\n| cover      = Soft Cell - Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1981|11|27|df=yes}}\n| recorded   = 1981\n| studio     =\n* Camden Cell, London{{efn|Except \"Tainted Love\"}}\n* [[Advision Studios|Advision]], London{{efn|\"Tainted Love\"}}\n| genre      =\n* [[Synth-pop]]\n* [[New wave music|new wave]]\n| length     = 40:32\n| label      = [[Some Bizzare Records|Some Bizzare]]\n| producer   = [[Mike Thorne]]\n| prev_title = [[Mutant Moments]]\n| prev_year  = 1980\n| next_title = [[Non Stop Ecstatic Dancing]]\n| next_year  = 1982\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Tainted Love]]\n | single1date = 17 July 1981\n | single2     = [[Bedsitter (song)|Bedsitter]]\n | single2date = 29 October 1981\n | single3     = [[Say Hello, Wave Goodbye]]\n | single3date = January 1982\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret''''' is the debut studio album by English [[synth-pop]] duo [[Soft Cell]]. It was released in the United Kingdom on 27 November 1981 by [[Some Bizzare Records]].<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Brian |last=Harrigan |title=Soft Cell's Bizarre Eroticism |magazine=[[Melody Maker]] |location=London |date=21 November 1981 |page=5 |issn=0025-9012}}</ref><ref name=\"NME19811128\">{{cite magazine |magazine=[[NME]] |location=London |date=28 November 1981 |page=43 |issn=0028-6362}}</ref> The album's critical and commercial success was bolstered by the success of its lead single, a cover version of [[Gloria Jones]]'s song \"[[Tainted Love]]\", which topped the charts worldwide and became the best-selling British single of 1981 in the United States\u2014as a result of the single's success, the album had reported advance orders of more than 200,000 copies.<ref name=\"NME19811128\"/> The album spawned two additional top-five singles in the UK: \"[[Bedsitter (song)|Bedsitter]]\" and \"[[Say Hello, Wave Goodbye]]\".\n\n==Recording==\nThe album was created on a limited budget; it was supposedly recorded almost entirely with a [[ReVox]] tape recorder, a borrowed [[Roland Corporation|Roland]] [[drum machine]] belonging to [[Kit Hain]], a small, preset Roland bass synthesizer, and an [[New England Digital|NED]] [[Synclavier]], belonging to producer [[Mike Thorne]].{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} The group caused some controversy in the United Kingdom over the song \"Sex Dwarf\", the music video of which was banned due to its explicit, [[Sadomasochism|S&M]]-related content.<ref>{{cite book |editor-last1=Irvin |editor-first1=Jim |editor-link1=Jim Irvin |editor-last2=McLear |editor-first2=Colin |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AVQbF9lTBwgC&pg=PA464&dq=Sex+Dwarf |title=The Mojo Collection: The Ultimate Music Companion |edition=4th |publisher=[[Canongate Books]] |date=2007 |page=464 |accessdate=7 August 2019 |isbn=978-1-84195-973-3 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Ruhlmann |first=William |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/non-stop-erotic-cabaret-mw0000651340 |title=Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret \u2013 Soft Cell |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=2 December 2005}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Larkin |editor-first=Colin |editor-link=Colin Larkin (writer) |chapter=Soft Cell |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=RA6-PA2005-IA42&dq=Soft+Cell |title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]] |publisher=[[Omnibus Press]] |edition=5th concise |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-85712-595-8 |accessdate=7 August 2019 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Fricke |first=David |authorlink=David Fricke |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/softcell/albums/album/118629/review/6068290/nonstop_erotic_cabaret |title=Soft Cell: Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=13 May 1982 |accessdate=17 August 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090501222332/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/softcell/albums/album/118629/review/6068290/nonstop_erotic_cabaret |archivedate=1 May 2009}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Rolling Stone#International editions|Rolling Stone Russia]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Bukharin |first=Andrew |url=http://www.rollingstone.ru/articles/7759 |title=Soft Cell \"Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret\" |work=[[Rolling Stone#International editions|Rolling Stone Russia]] |language=Russian |date=June 2009 |accessdate=3 January 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727120722/http://www.rollingstone.ru/articles/7759 |archivedate=27 July 2011}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]''\n| rev5Score = 4/5<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Scott |first=Danny |title=Soft Cell: Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret / Non Stop Ecstatic Dancing / The Art of Falling Apart / Last Night in Sodom; Marc and the Mambas: Untitled / Torment and Toreros |magazine=[[Select (magazine)|Select]] |issue=23 |date=May 1992 |page=85 |issn=0959-8367}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev6score = B+<ref>{{cite news |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv3-82.php |title=Christgau's Consumer Guide |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=9 March 1982 |accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\nReviews for the album were mixed. ''[[Melody Maker]]'' said, \"''Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret''... confronts clubland with its patchy past, rubs perspective in its pretty painted face and acts like it means nothing... Aggressively embarrassing, ''Cabaret'' is the brashest, most brilliant and least-caring indictment of pop music's bankruptcy I've ever heard. No compassion, no sorrow, no joy, it just faces facts and moves to the motions... Like traditional cabaret, the whole thing parodies true emotion and like the best subversive cabaret its shallowness makes those devalued emotions even more painful \u2013 the very real decadence of this album springs from its callous realisation of pop's impotency, and yet its bored resignation to the ritual.\"<ref name=\"MM\">{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Sutherland |title=Review: Soft Cell \u2013 ''Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret'' |newspaper=Melody Maker |location=London |date=28 November 1981 |page=16 |issn=0025-9012}}</ref> However, ''[[NME]]'' found the album's premise was hollow, complaining that \"the Soft Cell sex strategy should offer something spicy, rude and even a little wonderful... but Soft Cell are conceptualists who rely on too many preconceptions and play around with too many ideas to convince you of any personal energy or commitment... Soft Cell are very plain fare \u2013 unspectacular music and very drab and flat lyrics, wrapped in a hint of special promise which is never realised.\"<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite magazine |first=Gavin |last=Martin |title=Review: Soft Cell \u2013 ''Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret'' |magazine=NME |location=London |date=28 November 1981 |page=37 |issn=0028-6362}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''[[CMJ New Music Monthly|CMJ New Music Report]]'' included ''Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret'' on a list of The Top 25 College Radio Albums of All Time.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xkzZ53I3Fx8C&pg=PA12 |title=The Top 25 College Radio Albums of All Time |magazine=[[CMJ New Music Monthly|CMJ New Music Report]] |volume=74 |issue=5 |date=6 January 2003 |page=12 |issn=0890-0795 |accessdate=3 January 2011 |via=Google Books}}</ref> American magazine ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'' placed the album at number 66 on their list of The 100 Greatest, Gayest Albums (of All Time).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.out.com/entertainment/music/2012/03/19/100-greatest-gayest-albums-all-time |title=The 100 Greatest, Gayest Albums (of All Time) |work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]] |date=19 March 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref> It was also included in Robert Dimery's book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/steveparker/1001albums.htm |title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die |website=Rocklist.net |accessdate=3 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[David Ball (British musician)|David Ball]] and [[Marc Almond]], except where noted\n| headline = Side one\n| title1 = Frustration\n| length1 = 4:12\n| title2 = [[Tainted Love]]\n| writer2 = [[Ed Cobb]]\n| length2 = 2:34\n| title3 = Seedy Films\n| length3 = 5:05\n| title4 = Youth\n| length4 = 3:15\n| title5 = Sex Dwarf\n| length5 = 5:15\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| title6 = Entertain Me\n| length6 = 3:35\n| title7 = Chips on My Shoulder\n| length7 = 4:05\n| title8 = [[Bedsitter (song)|Bedsitter]]\n| length8 = 3:36\n| title9 = Secret Life\n| length9 = 3:37\n| title10 = [[Say Hello, Wave Goodbye]]\n| length10 = 5:24\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = 1996 remastered CD bonus tracks<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/release/non-stop-erotic-cabaret-uk-bonus-tracks-mr0000686841 |title=Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret [UK Bonus Tracks] \u2013 Soft Cell |website=AllMusic |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n| title11 = [[Where Did Our Love Go|Where Did Our Love Go?]]\n| note11 = B-side of \"Tainted Love\"\n| writer11 = {{hlist|[[Brian Holland]]|[[Lamont Dozier]]|[[Edward Holland Jr.]]}}\n| length11 = 3:14\n| title12 = Memorabilia\n| note12 = B-side of \"A Man Can Get Lost\" in the UK and \"Tainted Love\" in the US\n| length12 = 4:49\n| title13 = Facility Girls\n| note13 = B-side of \"Bedsitter\"\n| length13 = 2:25\n| title14 = Fun City\n| note14 = [[Marc and the Mambas]] B-side of \"