{"title_page": "Madras War Cemetery", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n[[File:War Memorial Madras.jpg|right|thumb|240px|Madras War Cemetery]]\n\n'''Madras War Cemetery''' is located in [[Nandambakkam]], [[Chennai]] (formerly Madras), [[Tamil Nadu]], India. It was created to receive [[World War II|Second World War]] graves from civil and cantonment cemeteries in the south and east of India where their permanent maintenance could not be assured.\n\n==Description==\nMadras War Cemetery is located on Mount-Poonamallee Road, [[Nandambakkam]], about {{Convert|5|km|miles|abbr=in}} from the airport and {{Convert|1|km|miles|abbr=in}} from [[St. Thomas Mount]]. The cemetery is open to the public.\n\nThe cemetery occupies {{Convert|2.75|acres|ha|abbr=in}}<ref name=\"RestingPlaceFallsVictim\">{{cite news\n|last=Sivaraman |first=R. |title=Soldiers\u2019 final resting place falls victim to official apathy |newspaper=The Hindu |location=Chennai |publisher=Kasturi & Sons |date=6 December 2017 |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/soldiers-final-resting-place-falls-victim-to-official-apathy/article21269494.ece| accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref> and contains the graves of 856 Commonwealth service people who died in the Second World War. It was established in 1952 by the Imperial War Graves Commission, which is now known as the [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] (CWGC), to pay tribute to the people of the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth nations]] who died in military service. The cemetery is maintained by the CWGC in partnership with [[Government of India]].<ref name=\"AreAllMemorialsReallyThrobbingWithLife?\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/Are-all-memorials-really-throbbing-with-life/article14795868.ece | newspaper=The Hindu | title=Are all memorials really throbbing with life? |work= |accessdate=29 October 2018  |location=Chennai, India |date=17 July 2007}}</ref> The cemetery is given to the CWGC under perpetual lease by the Defence Ministry.<ref name=\"RestingPlaceFallsVictim\"/>\n\nThe cemetery also includes Madras 1914\u20131918 War Memorial, which is situated at the rear of the site and is styled on the lines of a lawn cemetery. The memorial, which does not contain any bodies, bears plaques with the names of British and Commonwealth soldiers who died in both World Wars and the inscription; \"Their name liveth for evermore\". It bears the names of more than 1,039 servicemen who died during the [[World War I|First World War]] and whose remains lie in many civil and cantonment cemeteries across India, where it is not possible to maintain their graves in perpetuity.<ref name=\"RestingPlaceFallsVictim\"/> Commonwealth nationals whose remains were buried include 14 Australians and 5 New Zealanders.<ref>{{cite news | last = Sujatha |first = S. |title=Oz, NZ war heroes remembered in Chennai\n | newspaper = Deccan Chronicle| location = Chennai |publisher = Deccan Chronicle| date = 26 April 2012 | url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/chennai/oz-nz-war-heroes-remembered-chennai-875 |accessdate=19 Jul 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501183342/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/chennai/oz-nz-war-heroes-remembered-chennai-875 |archivedate=1 May 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n<!--THIS NEEDS EXPANSION TO INCLUDE OTHER NATIONS-->\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India}}\n* [[Victory War Memorial]]\n* [[Delhi War Cemetery]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{cwgc cemetery|145401}}\n* [http://www.chennaibest.com/discoverchennai/sightseeing/madraswarcemetry.asp Chennaibest.com \u2013 Monuments in Chennai \u2013 Madras War Cemetery]\n* {{Find a Grave cemetery|2232004}}\n* {{Find a Grave cemetery|1109882|Madras 1914\u20131918 War Memorial, Chennai}}\n\n{{coord|13.0143|80.1944|display=title}}\n\n{{Chennai Topics}}\n{{Cemeteries in India}}\n\n[[Category:Cemeteries in India]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Chennai]]\n[[Category:1952 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth War Graves Commission cemeteries in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n[[File:War Memorial Madras.jpg|right|thumb|240px|Madras War Cemetery]]\n\n'''Madras War Cemetery''' is located in [[Nandambakkam]], [[Chennai]] (formerly Madras), [[Tamil Nadu]], India. It was created to receive [[World War II|Second World War]] graves from civil and cantonment cemeteries in the south and east of India where their permanent maintenance could not be assured.\n\n==Description==\nMadras War Cemetery is located on Mount-Poonamallee Road, [[Nandambakkam]], about {{Convert|5|km|miles|abbr=in}} from the airport and {{Convert|1|km|miles|abbr=in}} from [[St. Thomas Mount]]. The cemetery is open to the public.\n\nThe cemetery occupies {{Convert|2.75|acres|ha|abbr=in}}<ref name=\"RestingPlaceFallsVictim\">{{cite news\n|last=Sivaraman |first=R. |title=Soldiers\u2019 final resting place falls victim to official apathy |newspaper=The Hindu |location=Chennai |publisher=Kasturi & Sons |date=6 December 2017 |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/soldiers-final-resting-place-falls-victim-to-official-apathy/article21269494.ece| accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref> and contains the graves of 856 Commonwealth service people who died in the Second World War. It was established in 1952 by the Imperial War Graves Commission, which is now known as the [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] (CWGC), to pay tribute to the people of the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth nations]] who died in military service. The cemetery is maintained by the CWGC in partnership with [[Government of India]].<ref name=\"AreAllMemorialsReallyThrobbingWithLife?\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/Are-all-memorials-really-throbbing-with-life/article14795868.ece | newspaper=The Hindu | title=Are all memorials really throbbing with life? |work= |accessdate=29 October 2018  |location=Chennai, India |date=17 July 2007}}</ref> The cemetery is given to the CWGC under perpetual lease by the Defence Ministry.<ref name=\"RestingPlaceFallsVictim\"/>\n\nThe cemetery also includes Madras 1914\u20131918 War Memorial, which is situated at the rear of the site. The memorial is styled on the lines of a lawn Cemetery. The memorial, which does not contain any bodies, bears plaques with the names of British and Commonwealth soldiers who died in both World Wars and the inscription; \"Their name liveth for evermore\". It bears the names of more than 1,039 servicemen who died during the [[World War I|First World War]] and whose remains lie in many civil and cantonment cemeteries across India, where it is not possible to maintain their graves in perpetuity.<ref name=\"RestingPlaceFallsVictim\"/> Commonwealth nationals whose remains were buried include 14 Australians and 5 New Zealanders.<ref>{{cite news | last = Sujatha |first = S. |title=Oz, NZ war heroes remembered in Chennai\n | newspaper = Deccan Chronicle| location = Chennai |publisher = Deccan Chronicle| date = 26 April 2012 | url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/chennai/oz-nz-war-heroes-remembered-chennai-875 |accessdate=19 Jul 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501183342/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/chennai/oz-nz-war-heroes-remembered-chennai-875 |archivedate=1 May 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n<!--THIS NEEDS EXPANSION TO INCLUDE OTHER NATIONS-->\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India}}\n* [[Victory War Memorial]]\n* [[Delhi War Cemetery]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{cwgc cemetery|145401}}\n* [http://www.chennaibest.com/discoverchennai/sightseeing/madraswarcemetry.asp Chennaibest.com \u2013 Monuments in Chennai \u2013 Madras War Cemetery]\n* {{Find a Grave cemetery|2232004}}\n* {{Find a Grave cemetery|1109882|Madras 1914\u20131918 War Memorial, Chennai}}\n\n{{coord|13.0143|80.1944|display=title}}\n\n{{Chennai Topics}}\n{{Cemeteries in India}}\n\n[[Category:Cemeteries in India]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Chennai]]\n[[Category:1952 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth War Graves Commission cemeteries in India]]\n", "name_user": "Baffle gab1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDescription:c/e. Done here", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madras_War_Cemetery"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Artsakh", "text_new": "{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Artsakh\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Artsakh (Density).svg\n| legend1         = Number of confirmed cases by province (as of 8 April): {{legend|#FCEED3|Confirmed 1\u20139}}<!--{{legend|#F2A88D|Confirmed 10\u201349}}{{legend|#E36654|Confirmed 50\u2013199}}{{legend|#E5354B|Confirmed 200\u2013499}}{{legend|#87353F|Confirmed 500\u2013999}}{{legend|#630606|Confirmed \u22651,000}}-->\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Republic of Artsakh|Artsakh]]\n| first_case      = [[Mirik, Azerbaijan|Mirik]], [[Kashatagh Province]]\n| arrival_date    = 7 April 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=04|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Artashat, Armenia|Artashat]], [[Armenia]]\n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 6\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|moh.nkr.am}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread in April 2020 to the [[Republic of Artsakh]] (a ''de-facto'' independent republic on territory ''de-jure'' part of [[Azerbaijan]]). The first infected person was from the village of [[Mirik, Azerbaijan|Mirik]] in the province of [[Kashatagh Province|Kashatagh]] who contracted the virus from [[Armenia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aysor.am/en/news/2020/04/07/artsakh-coronavirus/1681590|title=First coronavirus case recorded in Artsakh - aysor.am - Hot news from Armenia|last=LLC|first=Helix Consulting|website=www.aysor.am|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019-20 coronavirus pandemic data/Republic of Artsakh cases chart}}\n\n=== March ===\nThe border of the Republic of Artsakh with [[Armenia]] has been closed in order to prevent the virus from spreading to the unrecognized republic, which had its [[2020 Artsakhian general election|general elections]] on 31 March.\n=== April ===\n\nOn 7 April, the Ministry of Health of the Artsakh Republic reported about its first coronavirus case after one of two suspected case tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.am/eng/news/571021.html|title=First coronavirus case reported in Karabakh|website=news.am|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The person is from [[Mirik, Azerbaijan|Mirik]].\n\nOn 9 April, three people were tested, of whom two tested positive for COVID-19, though one of them is a citizen of [[Armenia]]. The local who tested positive had registered to vote in [[Moshatagh]] (near Mirik).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.am/eng/news/571557.html|title=2 out of 3 citizens tested for coronavirus in Artsakh have positive results|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At this point, all known cases in Artsakh were from the province of [[Kashatagh Province|Kashatagh]].\n\nOn 10 April, one of the two additional confirmed cases was from [[Karvachar]], [[Shahumyan Province|Shahumyan]], making it the second province in Artsakh to have a confirmed case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evnreport.com/covid-19/covid-19-daily-briefing-april-10|title=COVID-19 Daily Briefing (April 10)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April, in accordance with a decision taken by the Artsakh Republic\u2019s Special Commission on the Emergency Situation on 14 April, the free movement of people in the villages of Mirik, Moshatagh, Tsitsernavank, Karvachar, in the Kashanagh region, as well as the Verin Horatagh, Kochoghot and Haterk communities of the Martakert region were restricted to the administrative boundaries of the respective villages and regions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evnreport.com/covid-19/covid-19-daily-briefing-april-14|title=COVID-19 Daily Briefing (April 14)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{Graph:Chart\n | type = rect\n | width = 680\n | colors = #ff6346\n | legend = Legend\n | showValues = offset:2\n | xAxisTitle = Date\n | xAxisAngle = -40\n | yAxisTitle = No. of new cases\n | y1Title = New cases per day\n | x = 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr, 14 Apr, 15 Apr, 16 Apr\n | y1 = 1, 0, 2, 2, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Template:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Artsakh]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Artsakh]]\n[[Category:2020 in the Republic of Artsakh]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Artsakh\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Artsakh (Density).svg\n| legend1         = Number of confirmed cases by province (as of 8 April): {{legend|#FCEED3|Confirmed 1\u20139}}<!--{{legend|#F2A88D|Confirmed 10\u201349}}{{legend|#E36654|Confirmed 50\u2013199}}{{legend|#E5354B|Confirmed 200\u2013499}}{{legend|#87353F|Confirmed 500\u2013999}}{{legend|#630606|Confirmed \u22651,000}}-->\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Republic of Artsakh|Artsakh]]\n| first_case      = [[Mirik, Azerbaijan|Mirik]], [[Kashatagh Province]]\n| arrival_date    = 7 April 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=04|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Artashat, Armenia|Artashat]], [[Armenia]]\n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 6\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|moh.nkr.am}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread in April 2020 to the [[Republic of Artsakh]] (a ''de-facto'' independent republic on territory ''de-jure'' part of [[Azerbaijan]]). The first infected person was from the village of [[Mirik, Azerbaijan|Mirik]] in the province of [[Kashatagh Province|Kashatagh]] who contracted the virus from [[Armenia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aysor.am/en/news/2020/04/07/artsakh-coronavirus/1681590|title=First coronavirus case recorded in Artsakh - aysor.am - Hot news from Armenia|last=LLC|first=Helix Consulting|website=www.aysor.am|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019-20 coronavirus pandemic data/Republic of Artsakh cases chart}}\n\n=== March ===\nThe border of the Republic of Artsakh with [[Armenia]] has been closed in order to prevent the virus from spreading to the unrecognized republic, which had its [[2020 Artsakhian general election|general elections]] on 31 March.\n=== April ===\n\nOn 7 April, the Ministry of Health of the Artsakh Republic reported about its first coronavirus case after one of two suspected case tested positive for Covid-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.am/eng/news/571021.html|title=First coronavirus case reported in Karabakh|website=news.am|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The person is from [[Mirik, Azerbaijan|Mirik]].\n\nOn 9 April, three people were tested, of whom two tested positive for COVID-19, though one of them is a citizen of [[Armenia]]. The local who tested positive had registered to vote in [[Moshatagh]] (near Mirik).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.am/eng/news/571557.html|title=2 out of 3 citizens tested for coronavirus in Artsakh have positive results|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At this point, all known cases in Artsakh were from the province of [[Kashatagh Province|Kashatagh]].\n\nOn 10 April, one of the two additional confirmed cases was from [[Karvachar]], [[Shahumyan Province|Shahumyan]], making it the second province in Artsakh to have a confirmed case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evnreport.com/covid-19/covid-19-daily-briefing-april-10|title=COVID-19 Daily Briefing (April 10)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April, in accordance with a decision taken by the Artsakh Republic\u2019s Special Commission on the Emergency Situation on 14 April, the free movement of people in the villages of Mirik, Moshatagh, Tsitsernavank, Karvachar, in the Kashanagh region, as well as the Verin Horatagh, Kochoghot and Haterk communities of the Martakert region were restricted to the administrative boundaries of the respective villages and regions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evnreport.com/covid-19/covid-19-daily-briefing-april-14|title=COVID-19 Daily Briefing (April 14)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{Graph:Chart\n | type = rect\n | width = 680\n | colors = #ff6346\n | legend = Legend\n | showValues = offset:2\n | xAxisTitle = Date\n | xAxisAngle = -40\n | yAxisTitle = No. of new cases\n | y1Title = New cases per day\n | x = 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr, 14 Apr, 15 Apr, 16 Apr\n | y1 = 1, 0, 2, 2, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Template:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Artsakh]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Artsakh]]\n[[Category:2020 in the Republic of Artsakh]]\n", "name_user": "Alpha Centauri 5932", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_Republic_of_Artsakh"}
